  "prompt": "How did the saying, \"goodnight Vienna\" originate?",
  "response": "The origin of the phrase \"goodnight Vienna\" is somewhat unclear, but it is believed to have emerged in British English during the early 20th century. There are a few theories about its origin:\n\n1. One popular explanation suggests it originated during World War I or World War II, potentially referring to a situation where military operations or negotiations had reached an end or failed.\n\n2. Another theory links it to the idea of Vienna as a metaphorical place representing a situation that has gone wrong or reached a dead end.\n\n3. Some sources suggest it might have been a music hall or theatrical expression, possibly originating from comedy routines.\n\nThe phrase generally means that something is finished, over, or has come to an unsuccessful conclusion. It's used colloquially in British English to indicate that a plan or situation has completely fallen apart.\n\nWhile these theories exist, there isn't a definitive, universally accepted explanation for the exact origin of the saying. The precise moment and circumstances of its first use remain somewhat mysterious.",
